body:
I have "fixed" a couple of these issues. I'm thinking about pushing my branch to the accumulo repo vs my fork. That would allow others to check it out and see some of the errors. The approach I have been taking is:

1. If `ThreadPoolExecutor.submit` is being called and the resulting `Future` is not being captured, then change the method call to `ThreadPoolExecutor.execute`.
2. If `ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor` is being used, then:
    a. Do nothing if the failure of the scheduled task would not cause some type of error. For example if the task is logging something or updating metrics
    b. Check `ScheduledFuture.isDone` in some other location to see if the background task has completed (failed).
    
I used the following test to check that `isDone` will return true when the task throws an error. Note that `isCancelled` is `false` when an exception is thrown, `get` will not return, and `get(int, TimeUnit)` will throw a TimeoutException. `isDone` seemed the only way to check that an error is thrown.

```
  @Test
  public void test() throws Exception {

    final AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger(0);
    ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor pool = ThreadPools.createScheduledExecutorService(1, "test", false);
    ScheduledFuture<?> f = pool.scheduleAtFixedRate(() -> {
      if (counter.incrementAndGet() == 3) {
        throw new RuntimeException();
      }
    }, 1, 1, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isCancelled());
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isDone());
    Assert.assertThrows(TimeoutException.class, () -> f.get(900, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS));
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isCancelled());
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isDone());
    Assert.assertThrows(TimeoutException.class, () -> f.get(900, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS));
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isCancelled());
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isDone());
    Assert.assertThrows(TimeoutException.class, () -> f.get(900, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS));
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isCancelled());
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isDone());
    Assert.assertThrows(ExecutionException.class, () -> f.get(900, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS));
    Assert.assertFalse(f.isCancelled());
    Assert.assertTrue(f.isDone());
  }
```

I found that this test becomes extremely stable when I do:

```diff
@@ -197,5 +197,8 @@ public class FateIT {
   private static TStatus getTxStatus(ZooReaderWriter zrw, long txid)
       throws KeeperException, InterruptedException {
+    zrw.getZooKeeper().sync(ZK_ROOT, null, null);
+    zrw.getZooKeeper().sync(ZK_ROOT + Constants.ZFATE, null, null);
     String txdir = String.format("%s%s/tx_%016x", ZK_ROOT, Constants.ZFATE, txid);
+    zrw.getZooKeeper().sync(txdir, null, null);
     return TStatus.valueOf(new String(zrw.getData(txdir), UTF_8));
   }
```

This seems to fix the test. However, I don't know if it's enough to address any potential issues when actually running Accumulo. In other words, I don't know if this is merely a test bug that is fixed by this change, or if it's a problem with Accumulo itself.
